Package com.skopylov.ftry

Class Try<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.skopylov.ftry.TryAutoCloseable
      • com.skopylov.ftry.Try<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - type of Try's success result.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.AutoCloseable
    public class Try<T>
extends TryAutoCloseable
    Class to handle exceptions in a functional way.

    Try can be either success with value of type T or failure with an exception. In some way Try is similar to Optional which may have value or not. Use #isSucces() and isFailure() methods to determine current try.

    Try has static factory methods Try.of(...) for producing tries from ExceptionalSupplier, ExceptionalRunnable functional interfaces and CompletableFuture.

    Methods that return Try could be used for method chaining. 

       Try.of(...)
   .map(...)
   .map(...)
   .filter(...)
   .recover(...)
   .recover(...)
   .logException(...)
   .onSuccess(...)
   .getOrDefault(...)

    Be aware that these Try methods behave differently depending on success or failure. For example onSuccess(ExceptionalConsumer) method does not have any effect in case of failure and logException() does not have any effect for success.

    When Try becomes failure, the only way to get back to success is recover method. Try has a set of recover(...) methods to recover failed try to the success. You can invoke recover many times implementing different recover strategies. If some recover method succeeds, then remaining recover methods will not have an action/effect.

    Methods that do not return Try considered as final in the chaining. These methods are get(), getOrDefault(Object), getOrThrow(), optional(), stream() These methods will close AutoCloseable resources marked with autoClose() method. 

       Try.of (() -> new FileInputStream("path/to/file")).autoClose()
   .map(...)
   .getOrThrow() // <- this will close FileInputStream
